{"title_page": "Philip Coggan", "text_new": "'''Philip Coggan''' is a British [[Business journalism|business journalist]], news correspondent, and author who has written for ''[[The Economist]]'' since 2006. At the paper he authors the weekly [[The Economist#Features|''Bartleby'' column]] on work and management. He served as the editor of the [[The Economist#Features|Buttonwood column]] on finance before John O'Sullivan took over in 2018. Prior to joining ''The Economist'', Coggan worked for the ''[[Financial Times]]'' for 20 years, 1986 to 2006.<ref name=\"mediadirectory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/mediadirectory/philip-coggan|title=Media directory: Philip Coggan \u2013 Buttonwood columnist and capital markets editor|work=The Economist|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge|Sidney Sussex College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penguin.co.uk/authors/philip-coggan/22188/|title=About Philip Coggan|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> In 2008, Coggan was named \"Senior Financial Journalist of the Year\" by the [[Wincott Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wincott.co.uk/awards/previous-winners/senior-financial-journalist.html|title=Previous Senior Financial Journalist Award Winners|publisher=The [[Wincott Foundation]]|work=Wincott Awards|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> and in 2009 he was voted Best \"Communicator\" at the [[Business Journalist of the Year Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.lse.ac.uk/publicEvents/events/2012/01/20120119t1830vSZT.aspx|title=LSE Public Lecture: Paper Promises: Money, Debt and the new World Order|publisher=[[London School of Economics]]|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> The [[CFA Institute|CFA Society]] of the United Kingdom named him \"Journalist of the Year\" in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Award: Philip Coggan |url=https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21688920-award-philip-coggan |newspaper=The Economist |date=23 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n\n* Coggan, Phillip (1986, 2009). ''[https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/543/54319/the-money-machine/9780141980737.html The Money Machine: How the City Works]''. London: [[Penguin Books]]. {{ISBN|0141009306}}\n* Coggan, Phillip (2000). ''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3961322-easy-money Easy Money: How to Avoid the Pitfalls of Losing Everything and Making Nothing]''. London: [[Profile Books|Profile Books Ltd]]. {{ISBN|1861972938}}\n* Coggan, Phillip (2005). ''[https://www.bookdepository.com/Economist-Guide-Hedge-Funds-Philip-Coggan/9781846683824 The Economist Guide to Hedge Funds]''. London: Profile Books Ltd. {{ISBN|1846683823}}\n* Coggan, Phillip (2011). ''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13131661-paper-promises Paper Promises: Money, Debt and the New World Order]''. London: [[PublicAffairs]]. {{ISBN|1610391268}}\n* Coggan, Phillip (2013). ''[https://www.goodreads.com/en/book/show/18590389-the-last-vote The Last Vote: the Threats to Western Democracy]''. London: [[Allen Lane]]. {{ISBN|1846146895}}\n* Coggan, Phillip (2020). ''[https://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/more-philip-coggan/1136014377 More: A History of the World Economy from the Iron Age to the Information Age]''. London: The Economist. {{ISBN|1610399838}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coggan, Philip}}\n[[Category:British columnists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Economist people]]\n[[Category:British financial writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{UK-nonfiction-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Philip Coggan''' is a British [[Business journalism|business journalist]], news correspondent, and author who has written for ''[[The Economist]]'' since 2006. At the paper he authors the weekly [[The Economist#Features|''Bartleby'' column]] on work and management. He served as the editor of the [[The Economist#Features|Buttonwood column]] on finance before John O'Sullivan took over in 2018. Prior to joining ''The Economist'', Coggan worked for the ''[[Financial Times]]'' for 20 years, 1986 to 2006.<ref name=\"mediadirectory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/mediadirectory/philip-coggan|title=Media directory: Philip Coggan \u2013 Buttonwood columnist and capital markets editor|work=The Economist|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge|Sidney Sussex College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.penguin.co.uk/authors/philip-coggan/22188/|title=About Philip Coggan|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> In 2008, Coggan was named \"Senior Financial Journalist of the Year\" by the [[Wincott Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wincott.co.uk/awards/previous-winners/senior-financial-journalist.html|title=Previous Senior Financial Journalist Award Winners|publisher=The [[Wincott Foundation]]|work=Wincott Awards|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> and in 2009 he was voted Best \"Communicator\" at the [[Business Journalist of the Year Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.lse.ac.uk/publicEvents/events/2012/01/20120119t1830vSZT.aspx|title=LSE Public Lecture: Paper Promises: Money, Debt and the new World Order|publisher=[[London School of Economics]]|accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> The [[CFA Institute|CFA Society]] of the United Kingdom named him \"Journalist of the Year\" in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Award: Philip Coggan |url=https://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21688920-award-philip-coggan |newspaper=The Economist |date=23 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n\n* Coggan, Phillip (1986, 2009). ''[https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/543/54319/the-money-machine/9780141980737.html The Money Machine: How the City Works]''. London: [[Penguin Books]]. [[International Standard Book Number|ISBN]]: 0141009306\n* Coggan, Phillip (2000). ''[https://ww